      "Understand ACV vs. RCV. This is one of the most important distinctions in your policy. Replacement Cost Value (RCV) means your insurance pays to replace your roof with comparable new materials, minus your deductible. Actual Cash Value (ACV) means they pay the depreciated value, which accounts for the age and wear on your existing roof. The difference can be enormous. A 15-year-old roof on an ACV policy might only pay out 30 to 40 percent of the replacement cost. If your policy is ACV, consider upgrading to RCV before storm season if possible.",
